---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import DocsSidebar from '../components/DocsSidebar.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Docs — workflow"
  description="Full documentation for @digitaloutbreak/workflow — philosophy, command reference, file conventions, and FAQ."
>
  <Nav />

  <div class="container-page py-10 md:py-14">
    <div class="flex gap-10 lg:gap-14">
      <DocsSidebar />

      <article class="docs-prose flex-1 min-w-0">
        <!-- Breadcrumb -->
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mono text-xs text-[var(--color-fg-faint)] not-prose">
          <a href="/" class="hover:text-[var(--color-fg-muted)] transition-colors">workflow</a>
          <span>/</span>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">docs</span>
        </div>

        <h1 class="mt-3">Documentation</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          A drop-in workflow scaffold for AI-assisted coding. This is the full reference — the
          philosophy behind the design, every command in detail, every file explained, and the
          answers to the questions that come up after you've installed it.
        </p>

        <!-- Versions row -->
        <div class="not-prose mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-2 text-xs">
          <span class="pill !text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">v0.15.8</span>
          <span class="pill !text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">MIT</span>
          <span class="pill !text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">15+ agents</span>
          <span class="pill !text-[var(--color-fg-muted)]">~21 files installed</span>
        </div>

        <!-- =================== INTRODUCTION =================== -->
        <h2 id="introduction">Introduction<a href="#introduction" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          <strong>@digitaloutbreak/workflow</strong> is an opinionated scaffold for working with AI coding agents.
          It installs a small set of files into your project that gives any compatible agent —
          Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Gemini, Cline, Aider, Continue, Windsurf, OpenCode, and others —
          a shared understanding of how to work on your codebase.
        </p>
        <p>
          The scaffold ships four things you'll actually use:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>A global <code>/workflow-init</code> slash command</strong> that bootstraps any project through a 10-stage discovery flow.</li>
          <li><strong>A <code>/feature</code> lifecycle skill</strong> that runs the five-command loop for shipping work — <code>spec</code>, <code>load</code>, <code>start</code>, <code>review</code>, <code>complete</code>. You write the code in between.</li>
          <li><strong>A <code>/cleanup</code> skill</strong> for project housekeeping.</li>
          <li><strong>A <code>code-scanner</code> agent</strong> for on-demand quality, security, and performance reviews.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          And a set of context documents — <code>thesis.md</code>, <code>project-overview.md</code>,
          <code>coding-standards.md</code>, <code>ai-interaction.md</code>, <code>current-feature.md</code> —
          that auto-load into every session so the agent stops asking questions you've already answered.
        </p>

        <div class="callout not-prose mt-6">
          <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
            <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" />
            <line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12" />
            <line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16" />
          </svg>
          <div>
            <strong>Who this is for.</strong>
            <p>You work with an AI coding agent every day. You've noticed that you keep re-explaining your project's stack, conventions, and feature workflow each session. You want a repeatable structure that survives across agents, projects, and weeks of accumulated context.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- =================== INSTALLATION =================== -->
        <h2 id="installation">Installation<a href="#installation" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          One command, run once per machine. It installs <code>/workflow-init</code> globally —
          you'll never need to install it again.
        </p>

<pre><code>npx skills add DigitalOutbreak/workflow -g</code></pre>

        <p>
          The CLI shows you a picker of every AI agent detected on your machine — Claude Code,
          Codex, Cursor, Gemini, Copilot, Cline, Aider, Continue, Windsurf, OpenCode, and a dozen
          more. Press <kbd class="mono text-xs px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded border border-hairline">space</kbd> to
          toggle which agents you want it installed into,
          <kbd class="mono text-xs px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded border border-hairline">enter</kbd> to confirm.
        </p>

        <h3>Why <code>-g</code>?</h3>
        <p>
          Without <code>-g</code>, the <code>skills</code> CLI auto-detects scope — if you happen
          to be standing in a git repo, it installs project-local into <code>.agents/skills/</code>.
          That's the wrong scope for a tool you want everywhere. <code>-g</code> forces a global
          install into your home directory, where every project will see it.
        </p>

        <h3>Skip the picker</h3>
        <p>
          If you want every detected agent in one shot, add <code>-y</code>:
        </p>
<pre><code>npx skills add DigitalOutbreak/workflow -g -y</code></pre>

        <h3>Other paths</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Project-local install</strong> — drops into <code>.agents/skills/</code> in the
          current project. Useful when you want the skill checked into version control with the
          project:
        </p>
<pre><code>npx skills add DigitalOutbreak/workflow</code></pre>

        <p>
          <strong>Legacy CLI</strong> — pre-dates the skills ecosystem. Supports Claude Code, Codex,
          and Gemini only. Kept for backwards compatibility. See the <a href="#legacy-cli">legacy CLI section</a>.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== FIRST PROJECT =================== -->
        <h2 id="first-project">Your first project<a href="#first-project" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          Open your agent in the directory where you want to start (or where you want to drop the
          workflow into an existing project), and invoke the slash command:
        </p>

<pre><code>/workflow-init</code></pre>

        <p>
          That's it. The flow takes ~5–15 minutes depending on how much you elaborate during the
          discovery interview. At the end of it you'll have:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>The workflow files installed (root briefs, context docs, skills, agents).</li>
          <li>An optional fresh framework scaffold if you picked a Web project (Next.js, Astro, SvelteKit, or TanStack Start).</li>
          <li>Templates filled in with your actual answers — no more <code>&#123;&#123;Placeholder&#125;&#125;</code> strings.</li>
          <li>A <code>Now / Next / Later</code> roadmap drafted from your stack and strategy.</li>
          <li>A recommended first feature ready to <code>/feature spec</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          From there: <code>/feature spec</code> the first thing on your roadmap, and you're shipping.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== PHILOSOPHY =================== -->
        <h2 id="philosophy">Philosophy<a href="#philosophy" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          The opportunity with AI coding isn't to add another chat box on top of your editor. It's
          to remove the one task you do over and over: <em>explaining your project to a new
          session</em>. Every conversation starts the same way — "this is what we're building, this
          is the stack, this is the convention" — until you've trained the agent into the same shape
          for the hundredth time.
        </p>
        <p>
          A workflow scaffold solves that by writing the briefing down once, in a place the agent
          will always read. Then the agent stops being a stranger every morning.
        </p>

        <h3>What we explicitly reject</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Auto-firing agents.</strong> Slash commands and agents in this scaffold never run on their own. You invoke them. They execute. They stop.</li>
          <li><strong>Background daemons.</strong> Nothing runs after the install completes. Everything that happens is observable, in your editor, on your terms.</li>
          <li><strong>Lock-in.</strong> Twenty-one files. MIT licensed. <code>rm -rf .claude docs/context docs/specs</code> and you're back to a vanilla repo.</li>
          <li><strong>Framework opinions where they don't belong.</strong> The workflow is project-agnostic. Web, backend, mobile, library — the scaffold flow adapts to your project type instead of presuming one.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- =================== THREE LAYERS =================== -->
        <h2 id="three-layers">Three layers of context<a href="#three-layers" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          The most expensive thing an AI agent can do is re-derive what it already knew last
          session. The cheapest thing is to skim a document. So the scaffold structures context
          into three layers, loaded by need.
        </p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Where</th><th>When loaded</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Auto-imported</strong></td>
              <td><code>docs/context/*.md</code></td>
              <td>Every session</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Read on demand</strong></td>
              <td><code>docs/specs/</code>, <code>docs/context/features/</code>, <code>backlog.md</code></td>
              <td>When the task makes them relevant</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Executed</strong></td>
              <td><code>.claude/skills/</code>, <code>.claude/agents/</code></td>
              <td>When invoked (slash commands, Agent tool)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>
          The top layer is the briefing — short, stable, always loaded. The middle layer is the
          deep reference — only pulled when the agent's working on something specifically related to
          it. The bottom layer is action — slash commands and subagents that <em>do</em> things,
          invoked explicitly.
        </p>

        <p>
          This split is the point. If everything were auto-imported, every session would burn
          context on docs the agent didn't need. If nothing were auto-imported, every session would
          start with a cold-start interview. The three-layer split keeps the agent informed without
          being overwhelmed.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== PROJECT-AGNOSTIC =================== -->
        <h2 id="project-agnostic">Project-agnostic design<a href="#project-agnostic" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          <code>/workflow-init</code> asks you the project type up front — Web, Backend-API,
          Mobile-Desktop, or Other. Only the scaffold stage (Stage 2) is Web-specific. Everything
          else applies to every project type.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Web</strong> — optionally scaffolds Next.js / Astro / SvelteKit / TanStack Start with shadcn opt-in.</li>
          <li><strong>Backend-API</strong> — skips the framework scaffolder; brings its own (<code>cargo init</code>, <code>poetry new</code>, <code>uvicorn new</code>, whatever).</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile-Desktop</strong> — skips it too (<code>flutter create</code>, <code>npx react-native init</code>, <code>cargo tauri init</code>).</li>
          <li><strong>Other</strong> — pure scaffold-free path, just installs the docs and skills.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The coding standards file (<code>coding-standards.md</code>) ships with Web/TypeScript
          defaults. <code>/workflow-init</code> rewrites the stack-specific sections based on your
          actual stack pick. The other context docs are stack-neutral by design.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== /workflow-init =================== -->
        <h2 id="workflow-init"><code>/workflow-init</code> · 10 stages<a href="#workflow-init" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          The bootstrap flow. Ten stages, flat numbering (no 1a / 1b / 2a), each one skippable. Roughly
          5–15 minutes end-to-end depending on how much you elaborate.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 00 · Idempotency check</h3>
        <p>
          Looks for prior runs in the target directory — checks for <code>CLAUDE.md</code>,
          <code>AGENTS.md</code>, <code>docs/context/</code>, and friends. If found, offers four paths:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Resume</strong> — pick up where you left off in a partial run.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh</strong> — overwrite the workflow files but keep your filled-in answers.</li>
          <li><strong>Start fresh</strong> — nuke and re-install from scratch.</li>
          <li><strong>Abort</strong> — bail out.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Stage 01 · Pre-flight</h3>
        <p>
          Asks the project type. This single answer routes the rest of the flow: Web takes you to
          the scaffold stage; everything else skips it.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 02 · Scaffold (Web only)</h3>
        <p>
          If you picked Web, optionally scaffolds a framework: Next.js, Astro, SvelteKit, or
          TanStack Start, each with a shadcn opt-in. Non-Web project types skip this entirely.
        </p>

        <div class="callout not-prose">
          <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
            <path d="M12 2 L2 22 L22 22 Z" />
            <line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="14" />
            <line x1="12" y1="18" x2="12.01" y2="18" />
          </svg>
          <div>
            <strong>The scaffolder uses real framework CLIs.</strong>
            <p>It calls <code>create-next-app</code>, <code>create astro</code>, etc., with flags that pre-answer every prompt. If a framework CLI changes its flags, the scaffolder may fall behind — file an issue, we'll bump it.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Stage 03 · Install workflow files</h3>
        <p>
          Drops the scaffold files into the project. This is the "everything" stage:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>CLAUDE.md</code> / <code>AGENTS.md</code> / <code>GEMINI.md</code> — root briefs</li>
          <li><code>docs/context/</code> — the five auto-imported docs plus roadmap and backlog</li>
          <li><code>docs/specs/project-spec.md</code> — authoritative spec template</li>
          <li><code>.claude/skills/feature/</code> — the <code>/feature</code> action files</li>
          <li><code>.claude/skills/cleanup/</code> — the <code>/cleanup</code> skill</li>
          <li><code>.claude/agents/code-scanner.md</code> — the review agent</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Stage 04 · Discovery interview</h3>
        <p>
          Four buckets of questions: <strong>Identity</strong> (who you are, what you're building),
          <strong>Stack</strong> (frameworks, hosting, database, auth), <strong>Strategy</strong>
          (thesis, moat, first product, positioning), <strong>Surfaces</strong> (the views and
          screens you'll need to ship).
        </p>
        <p>
          Each prose question has an elaboration loop — you can think out loud, or jump straight to
          "move on" if you've nothing to add. Nothing gets saved until you've confirmed.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 05 · MCP decision</h3>
        <p>
          Recommends MCPs (Model Context Protocol servers) that would be useful for your stack —
          for example a Postgres MCP if you're using Postgres, a Stripe MCP if you mentioned
          payments, a Playwright MCP for browser-driven testing. Also asks an explicit "will you
          call external services?" question.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Crucially, it does <em>not</em> install MCPs here.</strong> The install commands
          are recorded in <code>project-overview.md</code> and surfaced at the very end (Stage 09)
          so the agent restart they trigger doesn't wipe the interview context.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 06 · Roadmap proposal</h3>
        <p>
          Drafts a <code>Now / Next / Later</code> roadmap based on your stack and strategy
          answers, iterates with you, then saves to <code>roadmap.md</code>. Skipped for existing
          projects with a populated roadmap.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 07 · Fill templates</h3>
        <p>
          Walks through every installed doc and replaces <code>&#123;&#123;Placeholders&#125;&#125;</code> with your
          actual answers from the interview. By the end of this stage your docs are no longer
          templates — they're your project's actual documentation.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 08 · Recommend first feature</h3>
        <p>
          Picks the smallest item from the roadmap's <code>Now</code> phase and offers to run
          <code>/feature spec</code> on it immediately. If you accept, you go straight into the
          feature lifecycle without breaking flow.
        </p>

        <h3>Stage 09 · Hand off</h3>
        <p>
          Surfaces the MCP install commands you decided on in Stage 05 — safe to restart now,
          because the entire interview is already on disk. Plus next-steps for the
          <code>/feature</code> lifecycle so you know what to do tomorrow.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== /feature =================== -->
        <h2 id="feature"><code>/feature</code> · the lifecycle<a href="#feature" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          The <code>/feature</code> skill is a five-command loop for shipping work. Each command
          is a separate action file in <code>.claude/skills/feature/actions/</code> — they're
          invoked by subcommand and run in fixed order. The actual coding happens between
          <code>start</code> and <code>review</code>.
        </p>

<pre><code>/feature spec   →   /feature load   →   /feature start
                                              ↓
                                       implement + verify
                                              ↓
History entry  ←  /feature complete  ←  /feature review</code></pre>

        <h3><code>/feature spec</code></h3>
        <p>
          Interviews you about the feature you want to build. Writes a per-feature spec to
          <code>docs/context/features/&lt;slug&gt;-spec.md</code> with goals, non-goals, design
          references (Figma, screenshots, Loom, etc.), and an implementation plan. The spec is
          the source of truth for the rest of the lifecycle.
        </p>

        <h3><code>/feature load</code></h3>
        <p>
          Pulls the spec file into the agent's context. Lightweight — just reads the file in. Useful
          when you've come back to a feature after a break and the agent needs the full spec, not
          just <code>current-feature.md</code>'s summary.
        </p>

        <h3><code>/feature start</code></h3>
        <p>
          Cuts a git branch named <code>feature/&lt;slug&gt;</code> (or <code>fix/&lt;slug&gt;</code> for
          bugfixes) and updates <code>current-feature.md</code> with the active feature's name and
          status. From here, you implement.
        </p>

        <h3><code>/feature review</code></h3>
        <p>
          Optional. Runs the <code>code-scanner</code> agent on the diff and reports issues across
          quality, security, and performance. Use it before <code>/feature complete</code> for
          anything non-trivial.
        </p>

        <h3><code>/feature explain</code></h3>
        <p>
          Optional. Generates a plain-English summary of the diff for the PR description, commit
          message, or your own future self. Reads <code>git diff</code> against the base branch.
        </p>

        <h3><code>/feature complete</code></h3>
        <p>
          Final step. Merges the branch into main, deletes the feature branch, and writes a history
          entry into <code>current-feature.md</code> with what shipped. Asks before committing,
          merging, or pushing — never destructive.
        </p>

        <div class="callout not-prose">
          <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
            <path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"/>
          </svg>
          <div>
            <strong>Bug fixes use a lighter path.</strong>
            <p>Bug fixes get a <code>fix/&lt;slug&gt;</code> branch and skip the spec / load / start ceremony — they're reactive, not planned. Cut a branch, fix, merge, delete branch. Only add them to the history if they're substantial (more than a day of work).</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- =================== /cleanup =================== -->
        <h2 id="cleanup"><code>/cleanup</code><a href="#cleanup" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          A housekeeping skill for routine project maintenance. Invoke it when you're between
          features and want a tidy state — removes empty directories, normalizes stale files,
          checks that the workflow files haven't drifted from their canonical state.
        </p>
        <p>
          Read-only by default — invoke with <code>/cleanup run</code> to actually execute the
          fixes it identifies.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== code-scanner =================== -->
        <h2 id="code-scanner"><code>code-scanner</code> agent<a href="#code-scanner" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          A project-local subagent for code review. Scans the repo (or just the current diff,
          depending on how you invoke it) for issues across three buckets:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Quality</strong> — dead code, anti-patterns, complexity hotspots, missing tests.</li>
          <li><strong>Security</strong> — exposed secrets, insecure defaults, OWASP-class issues.</li>
          <li><strong>Performance</strong> — N+1 queries, unbounded loops, missing memoization.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Lives at <code>.claude/agents/code-scanner.md</code>. Read-only — it reports findings,
          you decide what to fix.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== Project layout =================== -->
        <h2 id="layout">Project layout<a href="#layout" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          Every file the scaffold installs has a job. The layout is small enough to fit in your head
          once you understand the three-folder split: <strong>root briefs</strong> live at the project
          root, <strong>docs/</strong> holds the human-readable context the agent reads, and
          <strong>.claude/</strong> holds the agent-executable commands and subagents.
        </p>

<pre><code>project-root/
├── CLAUDE.md                     ← root brief · Claude Code reads this
├── AGENTS.md                     ← root brief · most other agents read this
├── GEMINI.md                     ← root brief · Gemini reads this
├── docs/
│   ├── context/                  ← AUTO-IMPORTED every session
│   │   ├── thesis.md
│   │   ├── project-overview.md
│   │   ├── coding-standards.md
│   │   ├── ai-interaction.md
│   │   ├── current-feature.md
│   │   ├── roadmap.md
│   │   ├── backlog.md
│   │   └── features/             ← per-feature specs land here
│   │       └── &lt;slug&gt;-spec.md
│   └── specs/                    ← READ ON DEMAND
│       └── project-spec.md
└── .claude/
    ├── agents/                   ← invokable subagents
    │   └── code-scanner.md
    └── skills/                   ← invokable slash commands
        ├── feature/
        │   ├── skill.md
        │   └── actions/
        │       ├── spec.md
        │       ├── load.md
        │       ├── start.md
        │       ├── review.md
        │       ├── explain.md
        │       └── complete.md
        └── cleanup/
            └── skill.md</code></pre>

        <p>
          The split maps onto the <a href="#three-layers">three layers of context</a>: root briefs +
          <code>docs/context/</code> are <strong>auto-imported</strong>, <code>docs/specs/</code> and
          <code>docs/context/features/</code> are <strong>read on demand</strong>, and
          <code>.claude/</code> is <strong>executed</strong>.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== Root briefs =================== -->
        <h2 id="root-files">Root briefs<a href="#root-files" class="anchor">#</a></h2>

        <h4>What</h4>
        <p>
          Three top-level files at the project root: <code>CLAUDE.md</code>, <code>AGENTS.md</code>,
          <code>GEMINI.md</code>. Each one is a one-page pointer that tells whichever agent is opening
          your project where to find the actual context (the docs in <code>docs/context/</code>).
        </p>

        <h4>Why three of them</h4>
        <p>
          Different agents look for different filenames by convention. Claude Code reads
          <code>CLAUDE.md</code> (and supports <code>@</code>-import syntax to auto-load other files).
          Cursor, Cline, Aider, Continue, Windsurf, Copilot, and OpenCode read <code>AGENTS.md</code>.
          Gemini-based tools read <code>GEMINI.md</code>. Shipping all three means collaborators on
          the same project can use whatever agent they prefer without re-scaffolding.
        </p>

        <h4>How to use</h4>
        <p>
          Edit the project-name and project-layout sections to match your repo. <strong>Leave the
          <code>@</code>-imports in <code>CLAUDE.md</code> alone</strong> — they're what makes the
          five context docs auto-load every session. If you change where the context docs live,
          update the import paths to match.
        </p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>For</th><th>How it loads context</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>CLAUDE.md</code></td>
              <td>Claude Code</td>
              <td>Uses <code>@docs/context/&lt;file&gt;.md</code> syntax to auto-import.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>AGENTS.md</code></td>
              <td>Cursor, Cline, Aider, Continue, Windsurf, Copilot, OpenCode</td>
              <td>Tells the agent to read <code>docs/context/</code> manually at session start.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>GEMINI.md</code></td>
              <td>Gemini Code Assist and Gemini-based agents</td>
              <td>Same as <code>AGENTS.md</code>, addressed to Gemini.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <!-- =================== docs/context/ =================== -->
        <h2 id="context-docs"><code>docs/context/</code> · auto-imported<a href="#context-docs" class="anchor">#</a></h2>

        <h4>What</h4>
        <p>
          Seven markdown files that load into the agent's context <strong>every session</strong>.
          They are short on purpose — the auto-import budget is small. Anything in this folder
          should be load-bearing across every conversation; anything that isn't goes in
          <code>docs/specs/</code> instead.
        </p>

        <h4>Why we have it</h4>
        <p>
          The biggest waste in AI-assisted coding is re-explaining things the agent already should
          know — your stack, your conventions, what you're working on. <code>docs/context/</code>
          ends that cycle. Once filled in, the agent walks into every session already briefed.
        </p>

        <h4>How to use</h4>
        <p>
          Three files determine whether the context is genuinely useful or just noise. Spend an hour
          on these on day one: <code>thesis.md</code>, <code>project-overview.md</code>,
          <code>coding-standards.md</code>. The rest fills in as you go.
        </p>

        <h3><code>thesis.md</code> · the strategic memo</h3>
        <p>
          A founder's memo. Why this product exists, the bet you're making, the moat that compounds
          over time, the failure modes you've already flirted with. Written in your voice, updated
          rarely. The doc you re-read when you're tempted to chase a satisfying problem instead of a
          useful one.
        </p>

        <h3><code>project-overview.md</code> · the polished summary</h3>
        <p>
          Diagram-augmented. Scope, stack, surfaces, decisions log, tech-stack table,
          definition-of-done. The doc that catches a new collaborator up in five minutes. Derived
          from the deeper <code>docs/specs/project-spec.md</code>.
        </p>

        <h3><code>coding-standards.md</code> · the style guide</h3>
        <p>
          Ships with sensible defaults for the stack you picked in <code>/workflow-init</code> — TypeScript
          strict, functional components, server components by default in Next.js, Tailwind v4
          CSS-config, Drizzle migrations. Edit it as you discover conventions you care about.
        </p>

        <h3><code>ai-interaction.md</code> · the rules of engagement</h3>
        <p>
          How the agent communicates and works on this project. Branching strategy, commit policy,
          what triggers <code>/feature</code> vs <code>fix/</code>, when to commit, when to push.
          Copy as-is — edit only if you've thought about it.
        </p>

        <h3><code>current-feature.md</code> · the working file</h3>
        <p>
          Empty by default. <code>/feature start</code> populates it with the active feature.
          <code>/feature complete</code> moves the entry to history. The agent reads this every
          session to know what you're actually working on right now. Don't edit by hand unless you
          know why.
        </p>

        <h3><code>roadmap.md</code> · Now / Next / Later</h3>
        <p>
          Phased plan. Drafted in Stage 06 of <code>/workflow-init</code>, lived in afterwards.
          <strong>Bug fixes don't go here</strong> — they're reactive. Refactors and chores only
          land here if they're substantial.
        </p>

        <h3><code>backlog.md</code> · deferred items</h3>
        <p>
          Categorized list of things that got cut from completed features. Acts as the input to the
          next roadmap-revisit conversation. Cleaner than scattering TODO comments across the
          codebase.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== docs/specs/ =================== -->
        <h2 id="specs"><code>docs/specs/</code> · source of truth<a href="#specs" class="anchor">#</a></h2>

        <h4>What</h4>
        <p>
          The deep, authoritative project spec. <code>project-spec.md</code> ships as the template.
          You can add sibling docs (<code>data-layer.md</code>, <code>architecture-principles.md</code>,
          <code>content-types.md</code>) as the project grows.
        </p>

        <h4>Why we have it</h4>
        <p>
          Schema, contracts, env keys, infrastructure decisions — anything detailed enough that
          loading it every session would burn context unnecessarily. <code>project-overview.md</code>
          is the polished summary the agent always sees; <code>docs/specs/</code> is the
          full-resolution version it reads only when the task touches system-level concerns.
        </p>

        <h4>How to use</h4>
        <p>
          Treat <code>project-spec.md</code> as your project's constitution. Write it deliberately,
          revise it when decisions actually change, link to it from <code>project-overview.md</code>.
          When the agent needs deep detail, it'll read this on demand.
        </p>

        <div class="callout">
          <span class="callout-label">Mental model</span>
          <p>
            <strong><code>docs/specs/</code> is your <em>constitution</em></strong> — slow-moving,
            foundational, evolves with the project. <strong><code>docs/context/features/</code> is
            your <em>session log</em></strong> — fast-moving, per-task, written and archived inside
            a single feature's lifetime. They look similar but serve opposite purposes; see below.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- =================== docs/context/features/ =================== -->
        <h2 id="features-folder"><code>docs/context/features/</code> · per-feature specs<a href="#features-folder" class="anchor">#</a></h2>

        <h4>What</h4>
        <p>
          One markdown file per feature you ship — written by <code>/feature spec</code>, named
          <code>&lt;slug&gt;-spec.md</code>. Goals, non-goals, design references, implementation plan.
        </p>

        <h4>Why we have it</h4>
        <p>
          A feature spec is too narrow to live in <code>docs/specs/</code> (which is project-level)
          and too detailed to live in <code>current-feature.md</code> (which is a one-page working
          summary). Per-feature specs are the persistent record of what a given piece of work was
          and why.
        </p>

        <h4>How it's used in the lifecycle</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><code>/feature spec</code> writes the file.</li>
          <li><code>/feature load</code> pulls it into context when you return to the feature.</li>
          <li><code>/feature start</code> uses it to summarize into <code>current-feature.md</code>.</li>
          <li><code>/feature complete</code> archives the entry into the history section of <code>current-feature.md</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The file itself can stay in the repo after the feature ships, as a record of what
          happened. Or you can delete it — the history entry in <code>current-feature.md</code> is
          the durable summary.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== .claude/ =================== -->
        <h2 id="claude-folder"><code>.claude/</code> · the executable layer<a href="#claude-folder" class="anchor">#</a></h2>

        <h4>What</h4>
        <p>
          Everything in <code>.claude/</code> is something an agent can <em>run</em> — not read,
          but execute. Two subfolders: <code>agents/</code> (subagents the main agent can delegate
          to) and <code>skills/</code> (slash commands you invoke directly).
        </p>

        <h4>Why we have it</h4>
        <p>
          Documentation tells the agent what to do; skills and agents are <em>how</em> it does it.
          Slash commands codify multi-step workflows (the <code>/feature</code> lifecycle, the
          <code>/cleanup</code> housekeeping pass) so you don't have to re-explain them.
          Subagents codify specialist roles (the <code>code-scanner</code> reviewer) so the main
          agent can delegate cleanly.
        </p>

        <h4>Why <code>.claude/</code> specifically</h4>
        <p>
          This is Claude Code's convention for project-local skills and agents. Other agents may
          look in different paths in future versions; for now, Claude Code is the only tool that
          reads from <code>.claude/</code> directly. Other agents still get the workflow benefits
          via the root briefs and <code>docs/context/</code>.
        </p>

        <h3 id="claude-skills"><code>.claude/skills/</code> · slash commands</h3>
        <p>
          Each skill is a folder with a <code>skill.md</code> manifest. If the skill has subcommands
          (like <code>/feature spec</code>, <code>/feature load</code>), each subcommand is a separate
          markdown file in an <code>actions/</code> directory. The agent reads the manifest to
          discover what subcommands exist, then reads the relevant action file when you invoke it.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong><code>feature/</code></strong> — the <a href="#feature">/feature lifecycle</a>. Six action files: spec, load, start, review, explain, complete.</li>
          <li><strong><code>cleanup/</code></strong> — the <a href="#cleanup">/cleanup skill</a>. Single action file for project housekeeping.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Skills are read-only by default — they describe the steps. Mutations (creating branches,
          editing files, committing) happen through the agent's normal tools and require permission
          the same as any other edit.
        </p>

        <h3 id="claude-agents"><code>.claude/agents/</code> · subagents</h3>
        <p>
          Each agent is a single markdown file describing a specialist role, the tools it has access
          to, and the focus of its work. The main agent invokes a subagent via the Agent tool when
          a task fits the subagent's scope.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong><code>code-scanner.md</code></strong> — the <a href="#code-scanner">code-scanner agent</a>. Reviews quality, security, and performance issues. Read-only.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Agents differ from skills in invocation style: skills are <em>commands you run</em>;
          agents are <em>roles the main agent delegates to</em>. A skill is a recipe; an agent is a
          contractor.
        </p>

        <!-- =================== Compatibility =================== -->
        <h2 id="compatibility">Compatibility<a href="#compatibility" class="anchor">#</a></h2>
        <p>
          Three agents have confirmed slash-command support via the <a href="https://www.skills.sh" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">open agent skills</a>
          standard. Many more read the root briefs (<code>AGENTS.md</code>, <code>CLAUDE.md</code>,
          <code>GEMINI.md</code>) and follow them to the context docs.
        </p>

