        <!-- =================== FAQ =================== -->
        <h2 id="faq">FAQ<a href="#faq" class="anchor">#</a></h2>

        <h3>How do I update to a newer version?</h3>
        <p>
          Re-run the install. <code>npx skills add DigitalOutbreak/workflow -g -y</code> overwrites
          the global skill files with the latest. Existing projects don't auto-update — re-run
          <code>/workflow-init</code> in a project to refresh its scaffold (it'll offer Refresh as
          one of the idempotency options).
        </p>

        <h3>Will this conflict with my existing CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md?</h3>
        <p>
          The idempotency check (Stage 00) detects existing workflow files and offers Resume /
          Refresh / Start fresh / Abort. You'll be asked before anything is overwritten.
        </p>

        <h3>Can I customize the skills for my project?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes — once installed, the files in <code>.claude/skills/</code> and
          <code>.claude/agents/</code> live in your project repo. Edit them freely. If you improve
          something worth sharing, copy the change back into the public scaffold and PR it.
        </p>

        <h3>Does this work without an agent?</h3>
        <p>
          The files are useful documentation on their own — <code>project-overview.md</code> and the
          spec template work as project docs regardless. But the value compounds when an agent
          actively reads them every session.
        </p>

        <h3>What if my framework isn't in the scaffolder?</h3>
        <p>
          Pick the project type closest to yours (or "Other") and the scaffold flow skips the
          framework-install step. The workflow files install regardless. Then bring your own
          framework setup.
        </p>

        <h3>How is this different from a rules file or instructions file?</h3>
        <p>
          A rules file is one document — it tells the agent how to behave. This is a system: rules
          (<code>ai-interaction.md</code>), strategic context (<code>thesis.md</code>,
          <code>project-overview.md</code>), tactical state (<code>current-feature.md</code>), and
          executable skills (<code>/feature</code>, <code>/cleanup</code>, code-scanner). The rules
          file is one layer. This is all four.
        </p>

        <h3>Where do I report bugs or request features?</h3>
        <p>
          <a href="https://github.com/DigitalOutbreak/workflow/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub issues</a>. Include the version (<code>v0.15.8</code> as of writing), the agent you're using, and the command that triggered the issue.
        </p>

